<BODY lang=3DEN-US style=3D"tab-interval: .5in" vLink=3Dblue link=3Dblue =
bgColor=3Dwhite>
<DIV>I was reading my iuniverse newsletter and there was an article =
about=20
searching for life on other planets. It was mentioned that the habitable =
zone=20
may be a bit larger than previously believed and that larger, =
shorter-lived=20
stars could also make decent candidates for life-supporting solar =
systems.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>One of the pre-requisites they seem to be searching for are planets =
that=20
exist in a "zone" where there could be liquid water. <BR></DIV>
<DIV>Now I am not a physicist, but doesn't the fluidity of water depend =
on more=20
than jus tthe distance from it's star and the heat from it? Wouldn't the =

composition of the atmosphere determine just how much heat is generated =
by the=20
star? Then there are the reflectivity of the surface, internal heat, =
gravity and=20
air pressure. Depending on the composition of the planet, couldn't a =
large=20
planet a long distance from it's star still maintain liquid water? =
Wouldn't a=20
planet with very little or no greenhouse gasses, little internal heat, =
and a=20
highly reflective surface&nbsp;be able to sustain liquid water in an =
orbit much=20
closer than ours? We wouldn't have any liquid water where we are without =
our=20
greenhouse gasses and/or with a much higher air pressure.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>It seems to me that the people conducting these searches are =
limiting=20
themselves by putting a "habital" zone around a star. </DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Anyways, am I way off here? I was just curious and I thought =
someone here=20
might know a bit more about this than I.</DIV>
<DIV>&nbsp;</DIV>
<DIV>Thanks!</DIV>
