<DIV class=3Dtexthead5>Boost Your Brain Power: Creatine, A Compound =
Found In=20
Muscle Tissue, Found To Improve Working Memory And General =
Intelligence</DIV><!-- BODY BEGIN -->
<P>Research undertaken by scientists at the University of Sydney and =
Macquarie=20
University in Australia has shown that taking creatine, a compound found =
in=20
muscle tissue, as a dietary supplement can give a significant boost to =
both=20
working memory and general intelligence. The work, to be published in a=20
forthcoming Proceedings B, a learned journal published by the Royal =
Society,=20
monitored the effect of creatine supplementation on 45 young adult =
vegetarian=20
subjects in a double-blind, placebo-controlled experiment.</P>
<P>"The level of creatine supplementation chosen was 5g per day as this =
is a=20
level that has previously been shown to increase brain creatine levels. =
This=20
level is comparable to that taken to boost sports fitness," explains Dr. =

Caroline Rae who led the research. "Vegetarians or vegans were chosen =
for the=20
study as carnivores and omnivores obtain a variable level of creatine =
depending=20
on the amount and type of meat they eat - although to reach the level of =

supplementation in this experiment would involve eating around 2 kg of =
meat a=20
day!" </P>
<P><B>Creatine power</B></P>
<P>Athletes and fitness fanatics have known that creatine =
supplementation can=20
increase sports performance and the compound - a close relative of the =
amino=20
acids - has also been trialed successfully in the treatment of =
neurological,=20
neuromuscular and atherosclerotic disease. "We know that creatine plays =
a=20
pivotal role in maintaining energy levels in the brain," says Dr. Rae. =
"So it=20
was a reasonable hypothesis that supplementing a diet with creatine =
could assist=20
brain function." </P>
<P>The experiment tested this hypothesis by giving the one group of =
subjects a=20
creatine supplement and a second group a placebo for six weeks, followed =
by a=20
six week period with no intake and a final six week period when the =
control and=20
placebo group were swapped. Intelligence and memory were tested at four =
points:=20
the start of the trial; the end of the first six week period; and the =
start and=20
endpoint of the final six week period. </P>
<P><B>Testing tasks</B></P>
<P>The effect on working memory was tested using a backward digit span =
test in=20
which the subject has to repeat in reverse order progressively longer =
verbal=20
random number sequences. Intelligence was tested using Ravens Advanced=20
Progressive Matrices - a methodology commonly used for IQ assessment =
involving=20
completion of pattern sequences. The test is a well validated measure of =
general=20
ability with minimal dependence on cultural factors. "Both of these =
tests=20
require fast brain power and the Raven's task was conducted under time=20
pressure," says Dr. Rae. "The results were clear with both our =
experimental=20
groups and in both test scenarios: creatine supplementation gave a =
significant=20
measurable boost to brain power. For example in the digit span test =
subjects=20
ability to remember long numbers, like telephone numbers, improved from =
a number=20
length of about 7 to an average of 8.5 digits." </P>
<P>The study shows that increased creatine intake results in improved =
brain=20
function, similar to effects shown previously in muscle and heart. The =
results=20
agree with previous observations showing that brain creatine levels =
correlate=20
with improved recognition memory and reduce mental fatigue. "These =
findings=20
underline a dynamic and significant role of brain energy capacity in =
influencing=20
brain performance," says Dr. Rae. "Increasing the energy available for=20
computation increases the power of the brain and this is reflected =
directly in=20
improved general ability." </P>
<P><B>A short term boost?</B></P>
<P>Long term supplementation with creatine has yet to be declared truly =
safe as=20
there have been reported effects on glucose homeostasis (the regulation =
of blood=20
sugar levels) and potential subjects with a medical history of diabetes =
were=20
excluded from the experiment. In addition taking the supplement can have =
some=20
antisocial effects. "To be frank taking the supplement can make you a=20
considerably less 'fragrant' person," says Dr. Rae. "However creatine=20
supplementation may be of use to those requiring boosted mental =
performance in=20
the short term - for example university students."</P><!-- BODY END -->
